BEGIN:VEVENT
ORGANIZER:NJNU Particle Physics
SUMMARY:Felix Kahlhoefer - Searching for sub-GeV dark matter
DESCRIPTION:The non-observation of evidence for conventional dark matter candidates such as WIMPs has led to a growing interest in less explored mass ranges. In this talk I will give an overview of the phenomenology of sub-GeV dark matter. I will explain how we can use cosmology as a guiding principle to identify interesting models, featuring for example resonant or forbidden annihilations or inelastic scattering. I will then discuss how to probe these models in laboratory experiments, with a focus on searches for long-lived particles in high-intensity accelerators like Belle II and searches for electron recoils in underground experiments like XENON1T.
DTSTAMP;TZID=/Asia/Shanghai:20211117T150000
DTSTART;TZID=/Asia/Shanghai:20211117T150000
LOCATION:Online
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
ORGANIZER:NJNU Particle Physics
SUMMARY:Matthew Buckley - Unsupervised Machine Learning in Astrophysical Data
DESCRIPTION:Large astrophysical surveys provide us with a wealth of data that has important implications for fundamental physics questions. Fully exploiting these datasets requires new techniques and approaches, including machine learning. However, it is difficult to completely simulate many astrophysical systems. As a result, unsupervised learning techniques can be particularly useful for these astrophysical questions. I discuss two applications of unsupervised machine learning to astrophysical data: discovering stellar streams and measuring the local Galactic density. 
DTSTAMP;TZID=/Asia/Shanghai:20211110T100000
DTSTART;TZID=/Asia/Shanghai:20211110T100000
LOCATION:Online
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
ORGANIZER:NJNU Particle Physics
SUMMARY:Gino Isidori - B anomalies and the flavor of SMEFT
DESCRIPTION:Recent data in B-meson decays indicate a coherent pattern of deviations from the Standard Model predictions. These 'anomalies' provide a perfect playground for using the Standard Model Effective Field Theory (SMEFT) in a bottom-up approach, not only to set limits on the scale of the New Physics, but also to extract precise indications about the nature of physics beyond the SM. I will discuss, in particular, how present data points toward new dynamics not far from the TeV scale,  possibly by linked to the origin of fermion mass hierarchies, and to the unification of quarks and leptons. Implications for future measurements both at low and high-energies are also briefly discussed.
DTSTAMP;TZID=/Asia/Shanghai:20211027T150000
DTSTART;TZID=/Asia/Shanghai:20211027T150000
LOCATION:Online
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
ORGANIZER:NJNU Particle Physics
SUMMARY:Ciaran O'Hare - Venturing into the neutrino fog
DESCRIPTION:The last few years have seen the largest underground dark matter searches rapidly approach their purported ultimate sensitivity limit, which is increasingly being referred to as the "neutrino fog". An experiment reaches the neutrino fog went it becomes so large and so sensitive that the background from coherent scattering of astrophysical neutrinos begins to masquerade as dark matter, thereby preventing any conclusive identification of a signal. The encroachment of the neutrino fog has driven an increase in interest towards a technique which has the potential to circumvent the limit entirely: directional detection. The technique aims to measure the strongly anisotropic angular distribution of the dark matter wind incident on Earth as we journey around the Milky Way galaxy. The potential for dark matter discovery with directional detectors greatly exceeds that of conventional detectors, so the concept is well worth investigation if we 1) want to extend the search for dark matter well into the neutrino fog, or 2) wish to confirm a potential signal of dark matter without relying on the controversial and systematic-prone annual modulation. While in practice directional detectors are several years away from being at a competitive scale, there several promising approaches under investigation. The CYGNUS collaboration in particular is developing a competitive global network of directional detectors using modular gas time projection chambers. I will give an overview of the status of neutrino backgrounds to dark matter searches and then describe ongoing work trying to bring the concept of directional detection to reality.
DTSTAMP;TZID=/Asia/Shanghai:20211020T150000
DTSTART;TZID=/Asia/Shanghai:20211020T150000
LOCATION:Online
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
ORGANIZER:NJNU Particle Physics
SUMMARY:Tilman Plehn - Forward and Inverse LHC Simulations with Neural Networks
DESCRIPTION:LHC physics is a unique field in the sense that we compare vast and highly complex data sets with precise first-principles predictions. Generative neural networks can supplement these simulations and come with conceptional advantages.  I will show how flow-based invertible networks can provide precision simulations with uncertainty estimates and a high level of control through a new, GAN-inspired architecture.  In addition, I will discuss how such networks can invert event simulations and unfold detector simulations or the QCD parton shower in a mathemacially consistent manner.
DTSTAMP;TZID=/Asia/Shanghai:20211013T150000
DTSTART;TZID=/Asia/Shanghai:20211013T150000
LOCATION:Online
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
ORGANIZER:NJNU Particle Physics
SUMMARY:Archil Kobakhidze - Gravitational instantons, CP asymmetry, and axions
DESCRIPTION:Quantum gravity effects are typically considered irrelevant for particle physics and its phenomenology. Contrary to this, I will argue that non-perturbative quantum gravity effects associated with charged gravitational instantons have significant implications for the understanding of the observed quantisation of electric charge and an additional CP violation within the Standard Model. More specifically, I will discuss how the coloured Eguchi-Hanson gravitational instantons invalidate the Peccei-Quinn axion solution to the strong CP problem and suggest that the genuine axionic solution of the problem must involve an additional companion axion. Some phenomenological and cosmological aspects of the companion axion model will be presented.
DTSTAMP;TZID=/Asia/Shanghai:20210929T100000
DTSTART;TZID=/Asia/Shanghai:20210929T100000
LOCATION:Online
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
ORGANIZER:NJNU Particle Physics
SUMMARY:Tracy Slatyer - Dark Matter Puzzles from Indirect Searches
DESCRIPTION:The nature and origin of dark matter is one of the key unresolved questions of fundamental physics. Astrophysical and cosmological data provide powerful probes of dark matter properties, although to date no signal has been confirmed. I will discuss a number of claimed possible signals of novel dark matter physics in astrophysical datasets, alternative explanations, and open questions, with a focus on the Galactic Center Excess in GeV-scale gamma rays.
DTSTAMP;TZID=/Asia/Shanghai:20210617T090000
DTSTART;TZID=/Asia/Shanghai:20210617T090000
LOCATION:Online
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
ORGANIZER:NJNU Particle Physics
SUMMARY:Jonathan Feng - FASER and Forward Physics at the LHC
DESCRIPTION:For decades, the focus of searches for new particles at the energy frontier has been on heavy particles and high $p_T$. Recently, however, new ideas have led to novel opportunities for discovery in the forward region with relatively fast, small, and cheap experiments. In this talk, I will give an overview of the physics motivations, including both BSM and SM physics; describe FASER, currently being installed at the LHC; and present a few new initiatives, including a forward LAr detector and the Forward Physics Facility.
DTSTAMP;TZID=/Asia/Shanghai:20210610T110000
DTSTART;TZID=/Asia/Shanghai:20210610T110000
LOCATION:Online
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
ORGANIZER:NJNU Particle Physics
SUMMARY:Nicole Bell - Dark Matter Capture in Stars
DESCRIPTION:The capture of dark matter in stars provides a cosmic laboratory in which to study the nature of dark matter particles and their interactions. We outline an improved treatment of the dark matter capture process, which correctly incorporates a number of important, yet previously overlooked, physical effects. We discuss observational consequences for capture in the Sun, white dwarfs and neutron stars.
DTSTAMP;TZID=/Asia/Shanghai:20210603T110000
DTSTART;TZID=/Asia/Shanghai:20210603T110000
LOCATION:Online
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
ORGANIZER:NJNU Particle Physics
SUMMARY:Leszek Roszkowski - Direct detection of dark matter - a theoristâs perspective
DESCRIPTION:Measurement of a signal in direct detection of a hypothetical particle constituting the dark matter in the Universe  would provide arguably the most convincing proof of its nature. The problem is that we do not really know what the dark matter is. However, we do have some very good candidates for it. I will discuss to what extent current and future experimental efforts will be able to verify our ideas and/or open up other perspectives.
DTSTAMP;TZID=/Asia/Shanghai:20210506T150000
DTSTART;TZID=/Asia/Shanghai:20210506T150000
LOCATION:Online
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
ORGANIZER:NJNU Particle Physics
SUMMARY:David Shih - New Paradigms for New Physics Searches at the LHC with Machine Learning
DESCRIPTION:In recent years, there has been growing interest and many new ideas for anomaly detection and model-independent new physics searches at the LHC, enabled by powerful advances in deep learning. I will give an overview of some of the recent progress in this direction.
DTSTAMP;TZID=/Asia/Shanghai:20210429T090000
DTSTART;TZID=/Asia/Shanghai:20210429T090000
LOCATION:Online
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
ORGANIZER:NJNU Particle Physics
SUMMARY:Marc Kamionkowski - The Hubble tension and early dark energy
DESCRIPTION:We've known since the late 1920s that the Universe is expanding. However, the expansion rate currently inferred from measurements of the cosmic microwave background now disagrees with that obtained from supernova measurements. Over the past few years, theorists have been exploring the possibility that this Hubble tension is explained by some new "early dark energy": a new component of matter that may have been dynamically important several hundred thousand years after the Big Bang.
DTSTAMP;TZID=/Asia/Shanghai:20210422T090000
DTSTART;TZID=/Asia/Shanghai:20210422T090000
LOCATION:Online
